  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** falls under **criminal legislation** in most jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. It is a serious crime because it enables criminal activity to continue by concealing the flow of illicit funds.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Criminal Offense**:\n   - Money laundering is explicitly criminalized under laws in most countries. For example:\n     - In the **United States**, it is addressed under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)**.\n     - In the **European Union**, it is covered by the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**.\n     - In **India**, it is regulated by the **Prevention of Money Laundering Act (PMLA)**.\n\n2. **International Standards**:\n   - The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Countries are expected to adopt these standards into their national laws.\n\n3. **Penalties**:\n   - Penalties for money laundering can include **fines**, **imprisonment**, and **asset forfeiture**. The severity of the punishment depends on the jurisdiction and the scale of the offense.\n\n4. **Related Crimes**:\n   - Money laundering is often linked to other criminal activities, such as **drug trafficking**, **corruption**, **fraud**, and **organized crime**.\n\n5. **Prevention Measures**:\n   - Governments and financial institutions implement **Anti-Money Laundering (AML)** measures, such as **Know Your Customer (KYC)** protocols, transaction monitoring, and reporting suspicious activities.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a criminal offense with significant legal consequences, and efforts to combat it are a key focus of national and international law enforcement agencies.",
